[ci] release test: fix to use small for test init (#55677)

otherwise the permission is incorrect

Signed-off-by: Lonnie Liu <lonnie@anyscale.com>

[core] Update base exception group tests (#55684)

Signed-off-by: dayshah <dhyey2019@gmail.com>

[core] Fix test_failure on windows (#55687)

## Why are these changes needed?
Mixing ray_start_regular and ray_start_regular_shared in the same file
can lead to unexpected behavior where cluster state can unexpectedly
carry over into setup for another test. Here on windows
*test_put_error1, test_put_error2,* and *test_version_mismatch are*
skipped so *test_export_large_objects* runs directly after
*test_baseexception_actor_creation* causing issues during its setup.

In a follow up will just create another test file for all basexception
related tests so they can use a shared cluster.

Signed-off-by: dayshah <dhyey2019@gmail.com>

comment.body:
_ðŸ’¡ Verification agent_

<details>
<summary>ðŸ§© Analysis chain</summary>

**Installing after a frozen install mutates the lockfile; prefer not to change lockfiles in CI.**

Current order runs a frozen install, then bun add which updates package.json/lockfile and re-fetches. This reduces reproducibility and wastes work.

[suggest_optional_refactor]
Minimal change (if supported by your Bun version): avoid saving to lockfile while still installing the dependency:

```diff
-        run: bun add @elastic/elasticsearch@"${{ matrix.elasticsearch-version }}" --dev
+        run: bun add @elastic/elasticsearch@"${{ matrix.elasticsearch-version }}" --dev --no-save
```

Alternatively (outside the selected lines), reorder and rely on bun add to handle installation:
```yaml
# Replace:
# - name: Install dependencies
#   run: bun install --frozen-lockfile
# - name: Install Elasticsearch ...
#   run: bun add @elastic/elasticsearch@"${{ matrix.elasticsearch-version }}" --dev

# With:
- name: Install Elasticsearch ${{ matrix.elasticsearch-version }} (installs deps)
  run: bun add @elastic/elasticsearch@"${{ matrix.elasticsearch-version }}" --dev
```


If unsure about Bunâ€™s flag support, quickly confirm:

---

ðŸŒ Web query:

```web
Does "bun add" support a "--no-save" flag to avoid modifying package.json/lockfile?
```

ðŸ’¡ Result:

**Yes, Bun supports a `--no-save` flag that can be used with `bun add` (and `bun install`) to avoid modifying `package.json` or the lockfile.** When you use `bun add <package> --no-save`, Bun will install the package to `node_modules` but will **not update** your `package.json` or save a lockfile[1][8][3][6].

**Key details:**

- The `--no-save` flag ensures that neither `package.json` nor the Bun lockfile (`bun.lock`) are updated during installation[1][8][3][6].
- This behavior is analogous to the same flag in npm and pnpm for ephemeral or temporary installs.
- This flag is documented for both `bun install` and is supported for `bun add` as well because both use the same install engine[1][8].

**Example usage:**
```sh
bun add lodash --no-save
```
This will install `lodash` into `node_modules` without updating the dependency list in your project files.

**Related flags and alternatives:**
- To save the package to `package.json`, use the default behavior or specify `--save`.
- For reproducible installs that update only the lockfile, consider flags like `--lockfile-only` (which always writes a lockfile, unlike `--no-save`)[8].

References:
- Bun CLI documentation on `--no-save` for install operations[1][8].
- Multiple project templates and community tools confirm `bun add <package> --no-save` is supported in real workflows[3][6].

Citations:

- 1: https://bun.com/docs/cli/install
- 2: https://github.com/oven-sh/bun/issues/7233
- 3: https://www.npmjs.com/package/swpm/v/1.10.2?activeTab=readme
- 4: https://community.latenode.com/t/understanding-the-save-flag-when-installing-npm-packages/24673
- 5: https://github.com/oven-sh/bun/issues/5856
- 6: https://crates.io/crates/nci
- 7: https://discourse.nodered.org/t/time-to-test-node-red-with-bun-again-it-appears-to-be-working/87007
- 8: https://bun.com/docs/install/lockfile
- 9: https://ant.design/llms-full.txt
- 10: https://beyondco.de/blog/using-bun-with-laravel

---



</details>

**Use `--no-save` with bun add to keep lockfiles unchanged in CI**

- The current steps install dependencies with a frozen lockfile, then run `bun add â€¦` which mutates your lockfile and busts the cache.
- Bunâ€™s `--no-save` flag (supported on both `bun install` and `bun add`) installs into `node_modules` without updating `package.json` or `bun.lock`.

Apply this minimal change:

```diff
     - name: Install Elasticsearch ${{ matrix.elasticsearch-version }}
-      run: bun add @elastic/elasticsearch@"${{ matrix.elasticsearch-version }}" --dev
+      run: bun add @elastic/elasticsearch@"${{ matrix.elasticsearch-version }}" --dev --no-save
```

Alternatively, you can collapse both into a single `bun add` step (which also installs other deps) if you prefer:

```yaml
- name: Install Elasticsearch ${{ matrix.elasticsearch-version }} (installs deps)
  run: bun add @elastic/elasticsearch@"${{ matrix.elasticsearch-version }}" --dev
```

<details>
<summary>ðŸ¤– Prompt for AI Agents</summary>

```
.github/workflows/quality.yml around lines 41-42: the workflow runs `bun add`
which mutates bun.lock and busts CI cache; update the step to use Bun's
--no-save flag so the package is installed into node_modules for the job without
updating package.json or bun.lock (or alternatively merge this into a single
`bun add` that installs dependencies and the elasticsearch package in one step).
```

</details>

commits.message:
Adds a new MQL5 Expert Advisor for MetaTrader 5 that implements a strategy based on the crossover of a Kaufman's Adaptive Moving Average (AMA) and a regular, slower Simple Moving Average (SMA).

The EA's trading logic is as follows:
- The AMA adjusts its speed based on market volatility, aiming to be more responsive in trending markets and less so in ranging markets.
- A buy order is triggered when the AMA crosses above the slower SMA.
- A sell order is triggered when the AMA crosses below the slower SMA.

The EA includes configurable input parameters for both the AMA and the slow MA, as well as standard risk management settings.

The EA is designed to execute its logic only once per bar.

issue.body:
**Bug Description**

When scanning a very large number of files (millions of files), the application becomes unresponsive and freezes. If I force-close the application while it is stuck, then try to reopen the `.exe`, the program immediately crashes (silent exit) and cannot be launched again.

**Steps to reproduce:**

- Open Czkawka (GUI version).
- Select a directory with a very large number of files (e.g., entire drive).
- Start scanning.
- Wait until the application freezes and becomes unresponsive.
- Force close the program.
- Try reopening czkawka_gui.exe.

**Expected behavior**

The app should either recover gracefully after scanning large file sets, or at least be able to start normally after a forced close.

**System**

- Czkawka/Krokiet version: 9.0.0 GUI
- OS version: Windows 11 x64
- Installation method: github binaries<!-- e.g. github binaries, flatpak, msys2 -->

Increase your usage at any time by registering your Amazon Q Developer app installation with your AWS account.

# Feature development

Amazon Q Developer allows you to generate code directly from natural language prompts. You can build new features, debug, refine algorithms by describing your requests and letting Amazon Q Developer perform the tasks. It can help to save time, reduce errors, and improve efficiency with code generation that evolves with your project.

# Code transformation

Amazon Q Developer transforms outdated codebases into scalable, efficient, and maintainable systems. You can update your technology stack, enhance performance, and ensure future compatibility while preserving the core functionality of your existing code. With Amazon Q Developer, you can avoid technical debt and build your applications for long-term implications.

# Code review

With Amazon Q Developer, you can automate code reviews within GitHub. When Amazon Q Developer performs a code review, it analyzes your pull requests, provides feedback on code quality, potential issues, and security concerns. Amazon Q Developer then provides suggestions based on the code review.


# Getting started

1. Select the GitHub repositories that can use Amazon Q Developer and complete the authorization process.
2. Get started using Amazon Q Developer in an issue by adding labels for feature development or code transformation, or by creating a new pull request for code review.
